# PreliZ

______________________________________________________________________

Adventures with [PreliZ](https://preliz.readthedocs.io).

<!-- truncate -->

```python showLineNumbers
import preliz as pz
```

:::warning

WARNING (pytensor.tensor.blas): Using NumPy C-API based implementation for BLAS functions.

:::

I'll start looking at continuous variables, specifically the
[beta](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beta_distribution). This one is great to start with
because when the parameters for the distribution $\alpha$ and $\beta$ both equal 1, then
we get a uniform distribution over the support. The **beta** distribution has the
mathematical form

$$
f(x\mid\alpha,\beta)=\frac{\Gamma(\alpha+\beta)}{\Gamma(\alpha)\Gamma(\beta)}x^{\alpha-1}\left(1-x\right)^{\beta-1}
$$

where $\Gamma(\cdot)$ is the [Gamma](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gamma_function)
function, and $\alpha$ and $\beta$ are parameters we can adjust. Below I have set
$\alpha=\beta=1$, which gives us a uniform distribution over the support (x-axis) of the
distribution.

```python showLineNumbers
pz.Beta(alpha=1, beta=1).plot_pdf(pointinterval=True)
```

\<Axes: \>

![](data:image/png;base64,)
\<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes\>

Another choice of the **beta** distribution is shown below. The "box plot" shows the 50%
highest density interval (thicker line) and the 95% highest density interval (thinner
line). Another cool thing about the **beta** distribution is that as
$\alpha\rightarrow 0$ and $\beta\rightarrow 0$, we get the
[Bernoulli distribution](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bernoulli_distribution).

```python showLineNumbers
pz.Beta(alpha=2, beta=5).plot_pdf(pointinterval=True)
```

\<Axes: \>

![](data:image/png;base64,)
\<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes\>

One of the coolest things about PreliZ is that you can determine parameters for a
distribution, by defining the maximum entropy interval.

```python showLineNumbers
pz.maxent(distribution=pz.Beta(), lower=0.3, upper=0.8, mass=0.8)
```

([1mBeta[0m(alpha=3.3, beta=2.8), \<Axes: \>)

![](data:image/png;base64,)
\<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes\>

So what does this mean exactly? Well, if I had data between 0.3 and 0.8, I could choose
a well informed prior that encompassed the data, but still had probabilities beyond
those values. To compare, look at what happens when the mass is set to 0.6.

```python showLineNumbers
pz.maxent(distribution=pz.Beta(), lower=0.3, upper=0.8, mass=0.8)
pz.maxent(distribution=pz.Beta(), lower=0.3, upper=0.8, mass=0.6)
```

([1mBeta[0m(alpha=1.49, beta=1.4), \<Axes: \>)

![](data:image/png;base64,)
\<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes\>

Comparing the two distributions shows that the one with the mass set to 0.6 between the
interval $[0.3, 0.8]$ has higher probabilities for sampling values between $[0, 0.3]$
than the distribution with mass 0.8.

```python showLineNumbers
pz.maxent(distribution=pz.Normal(), lower=0.3, upper=0.8, mass=0.6)
```

([1mNormal[0m(mu=0.55, sigma=0.297), \<Axes: \>)
